<div class="container">
    <h1>Understanding Objects in OOP</h1>
    <p>
        Remember in the <a href="@Url.Action("Classes", "OOP")"><strong>Classes</strong></a> lesson, we learned that a <strong>class</strong> is a blueprint or recipe?  
        An <strong>object</strong> is like the actual item we create from that blueprint.  
        Each object can hold its own data and perform actions defined in the class.
    </p>

    <h2>Example: Student Objects</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Creating Objects from the Student Class</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
// Class (blueprint) from previous lesson
public class Student
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }

    public void Study()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Name} is studying.");
    }
}

// Creating objects (real students)
Student student1 = new Student();
student1.Name = "Alice";
student1.Age = 20;
student1.Study();

Student student2 = new Student();
student2.Name = "Bob";
student2.Age = 22;
student2.Study();
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        👉 Let’s explain this step by step:
        <ul>
            <li><code>Student student1 = new Student();</code> → We create an object called <strong>student1</strong> from the <code>Student</code> class.</li>
            <li><code>student1.Name = "Alice";</code> → We give <strong>student1</strong> a name “Alice”.</li>
            <li><code>student1.Age = 20;</code> → We assign an age to <strong>student1</strong>.</li>
            <li><code>student1.Study();</code> → The object performs the <code>Study()</code> action, printing “Alice is studying.”</li>
            <li>We do the same for <strong>student2</strong>, but it has its own data (Name = Bob, Age = 22).</li>
        </ul>
        💡 This shows that multiple objects can come from the same class but each object has its own unique data.
    </p>

    <h2>Real-World Analogy</h2>
    <p>
        Think of a class as a <em>cake recipe</em>.  
        - The recipe itself is not edible — it just tells you how to make a cake.  
        - Each cake you bake is an <strong>object</strong>.  
        - Each cake can have its own frosting, size, and decorations, just like objects have their own properties.
    </p>

    <h2>Another Example: Products in an Online Store</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Product Objects</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Product
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public decimal Price { get; set; }

    public void DisplayInfo()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Name} - ${Price}");
    }
}
// Using Product class from Classes lesson
Product laptop = new Product();
laptop.Id = 1;
laptop.Name = "Dell XPS 13";
laptop.Price = 999.99m;

Product phone = new Product();
phone.Id = 2;
phone.Name = "iPhone 15";
phone.Price = 1299.99m;

laptop.DisplayInfo();  // Dell XPS 13 - $999.99
phone.DisplayInfo();   // iPhone 15 - $1299.99
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        👉 Here we created two <strong>Product</strong> objects.  
        Each product has its own <code>Id</code>, <code>Name</code>, and <code>Price</code>.  
        This is how objects let us model real things in a program while keeping data separate for each one.
    </p>

    <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Objects are instances of a class, created from a blueprint.</li>
        <li>Each object has its own data stored in properties.</li>
        <li>Objects can perform actions defined by methods in the class.</li>
        <li>Classes define structure, objects bring them to life.</li>
        <li>Real-world applications use objects to represent real entities, like students, products, or cars.</li>
    </ul>

